## Why This Is Asked

Tests involving background work and eventual UI changes are common in data apps. This question checks understanding of test isolation, idempotency, and end-to-end timing without flakiness.

## Key Concepts

- Background job queues and completion signaling
- API and UI mocking for determinism
- Data seeding and range validation
- Test isolation and deterministic timing

## Code Example

```javascript
// Playwright pseudo-example
const { test, expect } = require('@playwright/test');

test('export enqueues, completes, and provides download', async ({ page }) => {
  await seedDataForRange('2023-01-01','2023-01-31');
  await page.goto('/export');
  await page.fill('#start', '2023-01-01');
  await page.fill('#end', '2023-01-31');
  await page.click('#submit-export');
  await expect(page.locator('#progress')).toHaveText(/in progress/);
  await mockDelay(10000); // simulate 10s processing
  await page.waitForSelector('#download-link', { timeout: 20000 });
  const csv = await page.locator('#download-link').evaluate(node => fetch(node.href).then(r => r.text()));
  expect(csv).toContain('2023-01-01,2023-01-31');
});
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adapt this test to handle export failures and retry logic?
- What patterns help keep tests fast while still validating end-to-end behavior?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests spanning provisioning, data isolation, and cross-service consistency are common in multi-tenant platforms. This question probes practical orchestration, data lifecycle, and observability.

## Key Concepts
- Multi-tenant provisioning via API and on-boarding UI
- Per-tenant data isolation (dedicated schema/tenantId)
- End-to-end across auth, billing, webhooks
- Observability via logs, events, and DB probes
- Cleanup and idempotent teardown

## Code Example
